-- Australian, N.Z. Stocks: BHP, Rio, Lihir, Newcrest, Caltex, Healthscope
-- Sarah McDonald
-- 2010-06-25T06:40:22Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-25/australian-n-z-stocks-bhp-rio-lihir-newcrest-caltex-healthscope.html

          
          
             Australia’s  S&P/ASX 200 Index  fell
1.5 percent to 4,413 at the close of trading in Sydney. New
Zealand’s  NZX 50 Index  declined 0.5 percent to 3,034.11 in
Wellington.  
 The following were among the most active shares in the
market today. Stock symbols are in parentheses after company
names.  
 Mining shares: THE S&P 200 Materials Index, which includes
resources companies, dropped 1.71 percent on speculation
Australia’s incoming Prime Minister  Julia Gillard  will pursue a
new mining tax, even after she agreed to consult companies on
the plan that has sparked widespread protests among companies,
workers and politicians.  
 BHP Billiton  (BHP AU), the world’s largest mining company,
slipped 2.1 percent to A$38.80 in Sydney.  
 Rio Tinto  (RIO AU), the third-largest, fell 3 percent to
A$69.60. The company said there is “real uncertainty” in the
Australian investment environment.  
 Gold producers: Gold futures rose the most in a week after
the Federal Reserve said it will keep U.S. borrowing costs low
for an extended period, which may weaken the dollar and boost
the appeal of the precious metal. Gold futures for delivery in
August gained 0.9 percent to $1,245.90 in New York yesterday.  
 Newcrest Mining Ltd.  (NCM AU), Australia’s biggest gold
producer, climbed 1 percent to A$36.  
 Lihir Gold Ltd.  (LGL AU) gained 1.6 percent to A$4.44. The
second-largest gold producer on the Australian stock exchange
was raised to “outperform” from “underperform” at Credit
Suisse Group AG by analyst  Michael Slifirski .  
 Caltex Australia Ltd.  (CTX AU) tumbled 6.7 percent to
A$9.66. The company said it expects an after-tax profit in the
range of A$125 million to A$145 million for the first half of
2010.  
 Healthscope Ltd.  (HSP AU) slid 2.6 percent to A$5.21. CVC
Asia Pacific scrapped plans to team with Kohlberg Kravis Roberts
& Co. in a takeover offer for Australia’s second-biggest
hospital owner, the Australian Financial Review reported in its
Street Talk column, without saying where it got the information.  
 Macquarie Group Ltd.  (MQG AU) dropped 2.8 percent to
A$39.50. Australia’s biggest investment bank was cut to “equal-
weight” from “overweight” at Morgan Stanley.  
 Woodside Petroleum Ltd.  (WPL AU) declined 2.9 percent to
A$43.28. Australia’s second-largest oil and gas producer was
rated “sell” in new coverage at Citigroup Inc.  
